Incident

Incident and Problem Experience 
● Logs revealed unauthorized access by a user 
"thedarklord@hacker.com" who conducted 
brute-force attacks and successfully gained access on 
February 23, 2024, at 4:06 AM. 
● The unauthorized user deleted multiple records from 
the application database and made several 
consecutive 'POST' requests, editing the 'addon' paths, 
causing a critical error involving a missing module. Identiﬁcation and Analysis Resolution and Closure 
● A new VM was deployed with a backup image to 
restore service while investigating the incident. 
The addon paths were reverted, but some data 
remained corrupted. 
● The incident was closed after confirming the 
newly deployed environment was working and 
did not contain corrupted data.

Challenges - Incident Management 
● Time constraint of SLAs, did not meet 
RTO of 1 hour, spent time on analysis 
● Did not anticipate having to restore an 
image of the site, hence a backup was 
not created prior to the incident, 
hence we did not meet RPO

Challenges - Change Management 
● Ran out of Azure credits, VM kept 
on, DDoS Protection Plan 
continues running after turning VM 
Oﬀ
● Testing took too long 
● Eﬀectiveness of DDoS Protection 
Plan is inconclusive 
● Limited backup options due to 2 
VM limit, could not make a new VM 
for restoring an image. 
● Many restrictions due to limited 
permissions of student 
subscription (e.g. Entra ID)

Challenges - Communication 
● Not everyone has access to the Jira 
● Those who were in Jira had to update 
Jira tickets on behalf of someone else, 
misunderstanding/loss of information 
● Most of our communication was done 
in-person and through private chats, 
causing the Jira tickets to be lacking in 
details

Strengths 
(Incident Management) 
1. Followed ITIL incident management lifecycle and incident resolution process 
2. Report was highly detailed, with a chronological account of the incident from detection to resolution 
3. Investigation was thorough and methodical 
4. Used RCA techniques (timeline analysis, fishbone diagram) 
5. Eﬀective communication with all stakeholders

Strengths 
(Change Management) 
1. Detailed documentation of each step of the change management process 
2. Clearly defined when and under which conditions a rollback should be implemented 
3. Followed best practices in change management 
○ Proactive security measures 
○ Used modern cloud solutions to leverage its scalability, reliability, and security 
○ Validated changes through testing 
4. Backed up all relevant resources prior to the change after learning from incident management

Improvements 
(General) 
Communication plan: predefined templates for consistency and completeness of information. 
(Incident Management) 
1. Timeline Analysis: add severity level per event log entry 
○ Use colour codes to make it more intuitive 
2. Fishbone Diagram: 
○ More specific causes 
○ Relationships between causes 
○ Prioritise causes by their contribution to the incident 
3. Restore training virtual machine

Improvements 
(Change Management) 
1. What to test after rollback, who signs oﬀ after post-rollback testing 
2. Assess the potential impact 
○ Include a risk assessment 
3. Try implementing all changes on the relevant host machine prior to actual change 
○ Contingency plan in the case a security / testing measure fails 
4. Develop a plan for user training and awareness post-change 
5. Assess and document the eﬀect of the changes 
6. Formalise a process for regular updates and patch management

Conclusion/Learnings 
(Main takeaways) 
● Communicate more professionally 
● Deeper understanding of Microsoft Azure and Jira 
● Importance of security 
● Workings of a support team
